---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import StickyMenu from "../components/StickyMenu.astro";
import ProjectPage from "../components/ProjectPage.astro";
---

<Layout>
	<StickyMenu />
	<ProjectPage
		title="TOLTO!"
		images={["/game1.webp", "/game2.webp", "/game3.webp", "/game5.webp"]}
	>
		<p>
			TOLTO! is a psychological thriller where you search your estranged
			brother's apartment after he disappears.
		</p>

		<p>
			This is my first Godot game. It's a solo project, and I've created nearly
			everything myself; all code is handcrafted; all music and sounds are by
			me; ~90% of the 3D models and textures are original.
		</p>
		<p>
			I was drawn to games since it's a kind of cesspool for my interests. My
			academic background is in math and CS, but I have somewhat variegated
			interests. For instance, I've written literary fiction for a few years. My
			first artistic pursuit was music, which I began playing and producing at
			sixteen or so. I'm also passionate about visual art, and that eventually
			roped me into 3D work.
		</p>
		<p>
			Godot is a very lean engine. Because of this, I've had to implement plenty
			of necessary systems and tools. An important one I've made recently is a
			pipeline for fractured objects: with it, I mark a "base mesh" inside a <code
				>.blend</code
			>-file and all other meshes should be cell-fractured pieces of that base.
			A custom import script auto-creates the necessary scene inside Godot, so I
			don't need any manual intervention to create breakable objects. Another
			crucial thing is a material blending shader system, which uses the
			different UV channels in order to blend materials via image masks. Here,
			for the normal blending, I implemented reoriented normal mapping.
		</p>
		<p>
			Since this project contains so much, many thousands of lines of code,
			thousands of assets and sounds, etc., it's hard to give a comprehensive
			run-down. Some of the biggest challenges have been creating pipelines and
			system that make future work faster, like my modular weapon system, which
			works well now. I've also done a bunch of locomotion tweaking, making the
			character controller feel good, making the camera smooth. Animations are
			still only in their prototype stage, though, and there is a lot of room
			for improvements. The biggest thing I've learned while working on this has
			to do with over-arching game design, how to write for games, how to pace
			sections, challenging the player and their agency, forcing the player to
			make decisions.
		</p>
		<p>
			This game is not open-sourced, but my GitHub houses a few related
			projects:
			<br />
			<br />
			<a
				href="https://github.com/emil-ke/Ramosa"
				class="accentLink"
				target="_blank">github.com/emil-ke/Ramosa</a
			> — A Svelte Flow + Vite tool used to write branching dialogues, auto-exports
			into JSON.
			<br />
			<br />

			<a
				href="https://github.com/emil-ke/slippery-scenes-godot"
				class="accentLink"
				target="_blank">github.com/emil-ke/slippery-scenes-godot</a
			> — A Godot extension plugin for keyboard-based scene-switching which uses a fuzzy finding
			algorithm, inspired by Telescope.nvim. (Its GitHub page features a
			demo video.)
			<br />
			<br />
			<a
				href="https://github.com/emil-ke/go-to-last-scene.godot"
				class="accentLink"
				target="_blank">github.com/emil-ke/go-to-last-scene.godot</a
			> — Another simple plugin that mirrors vim's :b# command but for Godot scenes, i.e. you can hop between two scenes very quickly.
		</p>

		<p>
			The video below is a sort of poor-man's mechanics showcase I threw
			together in haste. The game does not have a trailer yet.
		</p>

		<iframe
			width="100%"
			height="500"
			src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/7BUq6BgTuzY?si=2As8pt9zXj7fY52r"
			title="YouTube video player"
			frameborder="0"
			allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
			referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
			allowfullscreen></iframe>
	</ProjectPage>
</Layout>
